--------------------------------------
The "Header" Stuff
--------------------------------------

    name: This is just a label. It doesn't do anything technical; it’s just the visual part which makes Ansible nice on the eyes.
    hosts: Who are we talking to? 'all' means everyone in my hosts file. Can be restricted during execution (on the command line) to a specific host or group at runtime without              modifying the playbook. Ex.) ansible-playbook site.yml --limit "host1,host2" 
    become: yes: This is the Sudo button. It tells Ansible, Do this as the rootuser by default. Can be combined with become_method: su (the tool used to switch users)                              and become_user: root ( who you want to become can be any user)
    vars: This is used to store data, manage system variations, and make playbooks reusable across different environments.

    vars: This is a Variable. Instead of typing your IP address 10 times, you save it here once so you can change it easily later.

--------------------------------------
The "Action" Words (The Tasks)
--------------------------------------

Inside each task, you see words like user, state, and key. These change depending on which Module you are using

--------------------------------------
#1. Industrial Deployment of Salt Minion
--------------------------------------

    vars: 
          salt_master_ip: This is a Variable. Instead of typing the Masters IP address 10 times, you save it here once so you can change it easily later.

--------------------------------------
#2. authorized_key (The Key Deliverer)
--------------------------------------
-name:    
 ansible.posix.authorized_key: ansible - The main software. posix - It basically means this tool works on standard Linux systems like Fedora, Ubuntu, and macOS. Authorized_key - This is the specific tool that handles SSH keys. This module name itself is a fixed command that Ansible needs to understand what you want to do, it cannot be changed.

    user: Which person’s pocket are we putting the key into? (On my VM, it's user).

    state: present: This is a big one. It means "Make sure this exists." If the key is already there, do nothing. If it’s missing, put it there. Can be put to absent as well which means make usre it is removed or deleted.

    key: The actual "Digital ID" data we are handing over. It basically read your local SSH public key {{ lookup ('file', '~/.ssh/id_ed25519.pub') }} and copy its contents to remote servers, enabling passwordless SSH access. The .ssh to .pb is where my public key is located.

--------------------------------------
#3. Salt Deployment Block; dnf (The Package Manager)
--------------------------------------

    state: latest: This means "Check for the newest version and install it." If it’s already the newest, do nothing.

--------------------------------------
#4. lineinfile (The Text Editor)
--------------------------------------

    path: Which file are we opening?
    regexp: (Regular Expression) This is a search. It tells Ansible: "Look for a line that looks like master:."
    line: This is what we want the line to actually say. If the line is different, Ansible deletes it and writes this one.

--------------------------------------
#5. firewalld (The Security Guard)
--------------------------------------

    port: Which "window" are we opening? (4505/4506).
    permanent: yes: "Keep this open even if the computer restarts."
    immediate: yes: "Open it right now, don't wait for a reboot."

--------------------------------------
#7. command (The Raw Shell)
--------------------------------------

    register: This tells Ansible to save the result of the command into a "folder" (a variable) so we can look at it later.
    failed_when: This is the logic. We tell Ansible: "If the word 'succeeded' isn't in the report, then mark this task as a failure."

--------------------------------------
The "Logic" Words
--------------------------------------

    block: Groups a bunch of tasks together so they share the same rules.
    rescue: This is the "Plan B." It only runs if the block above it fails.
    notify: This is a "Hey, remind me later" tag. It tells Ansible: "If I changed this file, I need to restart the service at the very end."
    handlers: This is where those "reminders" live. It’s a special task that only runs if a notify was triggered.

--------------------------------------
Summary
--------------------------------------

Most of these words describe a Desired State. Instead of telling the computer HOW to do it (like a script), you are telling it WHAT it should look like (state: present, state: enabled).
Does that make the "code" look more like a simple set of instructions now?
